Load Data

Read in the data.

data_url <- 'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jyurko/CS_1675_Fall_2020/master/HW/final_project/cs_1675_final_project_data.csv'

df_raw <- readr::read_csv(data_url, col_names = TRUE)
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   xA = col_character(),

##   x01 = col_double(),

##   x08 = col_double(),
##   x09 = col_double(),
##   x10 = col_double(),
##   x11 = col_double(),
##   response_1 = col_double(),
##   outcome_2 = col_character()
## )

Separate the variables associated with Step 1.

df_step1_inputs <- df_raw %>% select(xA, xB, x01:x06, response_1)

Separate the variables associated with the Option B classification formulation. The outcome_2 variable is converted to a factor with a specific ordering of the levels. This ordering is used when modeling in caret to make sure everyone predicts the Fail class as the positive class in the confusion matrix.

df_step2_B_inputs <- df_raw %>% select(xA, xB, response_1, x07:x11, outcome_2) %>% 
  mutate(outcome_2 = factor(outcome_2, levels = c('Fail', 'Pass')))

Separate the variables associated with the Option A classification formulation. The outcome_2 variable is again converted to a factor with a specific ordering of the levels.

df_step2_A_inputs <- df_raw %>% select(xA, xB, x01:x11, outcome_2) %>% 
  mutate(outcome_2 = factor(outcome_2, levels = c('Fail', 'Pass')))

Change data types for the whole data frame to perform EDA.

df <- df_raw %>% 
  mutate(xA = as.factor(xA),
         xB = as.factor(xB),
         outcome_2 = factor(outcome_2, levels = c('Fail', 'Pass')))

Standardize the data.

get_standardized <- function(df) {
  predict(preProcess(df, method = c('center', 'scale')), df) 
}

Fit Linear Models

Set the variables

Input data set

Define a data set to train on.

df_input <- df_step2_B_inputs

We train classification on step 2B inputs.

Resampling Scheme

Define a resampling scheme.

my_ctrl <- trainControl(method = 'repeatedcv',
                        number = 5,
                        repeats = 3,
                        summaryFunction = twoClassSummary,
                        classProbs = TRUE,
                        savePredictions = TRUE)

I will use repeated cross-validation by specifying the number of repeats to be 3 and number of folds to be 5. Thus, the models will be trained and tested a total of 15 times.

Performance Metric

Define a primary performance metric.

reg_metric <- 'ROC'

ROC is used for this part of the project.

Preprocessing scheme

Define pre-processing scheme.

prep_scheme <- c('center', 'scale')

I want to standardize the input.

Fitting the Models

Linear additive model (method=lm)

Provides a baseline comparison to the other models.

set.seed(1234)
fit_glm <- train(outcome_2 ~ .,

Tune the Neural Network.

size is the number of units in hidden layer (nnet fit a single hidden layer neural network) and decay is the regularization parameter to avoid over-fitting.

set.seed(1234)
nnet_grid <- expand.grid(size = seq(from = 1, to = 10, by = 1),
                         decay = c(1e-4, 0.1, 0.5))

fit_nnet_tuned <- train(outcome_2 ~ ., 
                  data = df_input,
                  tuneGrid = nnet_grid,

                  metric = reg_metric,

Random forest (RF)

The random forest model creates 500 bagged tree models. Compared to a standard bagged tree model, the random forest randomly selects the number of features to consider during the splitting process.

Train the standard Random Forest.

set.seed(1234)
fit_rf <- train(outcome_2 ~ ., 
                data = df_input,

Tune the Gradient Booster Tree model.

  • nrounds controls the maximum number of iterations. For classification, it is similar to the number of trees to grow.

  • eta controls the learning rate, i.e., the rate at which our model learns patterns in data. After every round, it shrinks the feature weights to reach the best optimum. Lower eta leads to slower computation. It must be supported by increase in nrounds.

  • max_depth controls the depth of the tree.

  • gamma controls regularization (or prevents overfitting). Higher the value, higher the regularization. Regularization means penalizing large coefficients which dont improve the models performance. The default is 0 which means no regularization.

  • colsample_bytree controls the number of features (variables) supplied to a tree. Typically, its values lie between (0.5,0.9).

  • min_child_weight, in regression, it refers to the minimum number of instances required in a child node. In classification, if the leaf node has a minimum sum of instance weight (calculated by second order partial derivative) lower than min_child_weight, the tree splitting stops. In other words, it blocks the potential feature interactions to prevent overfitting.

  • subsample controls the number of samples (observations) supplied to a tree. Typically, its values lie between (0.5-0.8).

I will hold all the parameters constant except for nrounds, max_depth, and eta.

set.seed(1234)
xgb_grid <- expand.grid(nrounds = seq(from = 10, to = 50, by = 10), 
                        max_depth = seq(from = 1, to = 6, by = 1), 
                        eta = seq(from = 0.1, to = 0.8, by = 0.1), 
                        gamma = 0, 
                        colsample_bytree = 0.8, 
                        min_child_weight = 1,
                        subsample = 1)

fit_xgb_tuned <- train(outcome_2 ~ ., 
                      data = df_input,
                       tuneGrid = xgb_grid,
                       method = 'xgbTree',
                       metric = reg_metric,
                       trControl = my_ctrl)

Tune the Support Vector Machine.

C is a regularization parameter that controls the trade off between a low training error and a low testing error (generalizability).

sigma (or sometimes gamma) parameter defines how far the influence of a single training example reaches, with low values meaning far and high values meaning close.

set.seed(1234)
svm_grid <- expand.grid(C = seq(from = 0.1, to = 2, by = 0.2),
                        sigma = seq(from = 0.01, to = 0.1, by = 0.02))

fit_svm_tuned <- train(outcome_2 ~ ., 
                data = df_input,
                 tuneGrid = svm_grid,
                 method = 'svmRadial',

Assemble the ROC curves for comparison.

cv_pred_results <- fit_glm$pred %>% tbl_df() %>%
  filter(parameter == fit_glm$bestTune$parameter) %>%
  select(pred, obs, Fail, Pass, rowIndex, Resample) %>%
  mutate(model_name = "GLM") %>%
  bind_rows(
    fit_elastic_add$pred %>% tbl_df() %>%
      filter(
        alpha %in% fit_elastic_add$bestTune$alpha,
        lambda %in% fit_elastic_add$bestTune$lambda
      ) %>%
      select(pred, obs, Fail, Pass, rowIndex, Resample) %>%
      mutate(model_name = "GLMNET_ADD")
  ) %>%
  bind_rows(
    fit_elastic_pairs$pred %>% tbl_df() %>%
      filter(
        alpha %in% fit_elastic_pairs$bestTune$alpha,
        lambda %in% fit_elastic_pairs$bestTune$lambda
      ) %>%
      select(pred, obs, Fail, Pass, rowIndex, Resample) %>%
      mutate(model_name = "GLMNET_PAIRS")
  ) %>%
  bind_rows(
    fit_elastic_triplets$pred %>% tbl_df() %>%
      filter(
        alpha %in% fit_elastic_triplets$bestTune$alpha,
        lambda %in% fit_elastic_triplets$bestTune$lambda
      ) %>%
      select(pred, obs, Fail, Pass, rowIndex, Resample) %>%
      mutate(model_name = "GLMNET_TRIPLETS")
  ) %>%
  bind_rows(
    fit_rf$pred %>% tbl_df() %>%
      filter(mtry == fit_rf$bestTune$mtry) %>%
      select(pred, obs, Fail, Pass, rowIndex, Resample) %>%
      mutate(model_name = "RF")
  ) %>%
  bind_rows(
    fit_nnet$pred %>% tbl_df() %>%
      filter(
        size == fit_nnet$bestTune$size,
        decay == fit_nnet$bestTune$decay
      ) %>%
      select(pred, obs, Fail, Pass, rowIndex, Resample) %>%
      mutate(model_name = "NNET")
  ) %>%
  bind_rows(
    fit_nnet_tuned$pred %>% tbl_df() %>%
      filter(
        size == fit_nnet_tuned$bestTune$size,
        decay == fit_nnet_tuned$bestTune$decay
      ) %>%
      select(pred, obs, Fail, Pass, rowIndex, Resample) %>%
      mutate(model_name = "NNET_tuned")

Gradient Boosted Tree (tuned) performed the best. The next best are Neural Network (tuned), Random Forest (tuned), Random Forest (default), Gradient Boosted Tree (default), Neural Network (default), and GAM. SVMs seem to be a little worse than the models listed above.

Which model is the best?

Gradient Boosted Tree (tuned) - the final values used for the model were nrounds = 20, max_depth = 5, eta = 0.2, gamma = 0, colsample_bytree = 0.8, min_child_weight = 1 and subsample = 1 - ended up to be the best model based on the plot because it has the highest accuracy. The next best by the one standard error rule are Neural Network (tuned), Random Forest (tuned), Random Forest, and Gradient Boosted Tree. GAM also performed well.
